# .env.example
#
# Optional configuration for scripts/claude_session_ping.sh.
# The script works out of the box with no config file at all (it just
# calls `claude -p` directly). Use this file only if you want to override
# that default behavior: send the ping elsewhere, customize the message,
# or fake the current time for testing.
#
# Copy this file to .env in the project root and uncomment/adjust what you
# need. (A CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_ENV_FILE override, if set, takes precedence —
# e.g. to keep using the legacy ~/.claude-session-ping.env path instead.)

# Example: use the Claude CLI directly.
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_COMMAND='claude --print "keepalive ping"'

# Or send to an HTTP endpoint instead.
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_URL='https://example.com/claude-ping'

# Optional message body.
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_MESSAGE='keepalive ping'

# Optional: override the current time for testing.
# Example: test the 11:11 trigger without waiting for real time.
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_MOCK_TIME='11:11'

# Optional: override where the ping log, schedule state, and Telegram bot
# log are written. All three default to project-local paths (logs/,
# .claude-session-ping/state.json, logs/) so these are rarely needed.
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_LOG='/path/to/claude-session-ping.log'
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_STATE_FILE='/path/to/state.json'
# CLAUDE_SESSION_PING_TELEGRAM_BOT_LOG='/path/to/claude-session-ping-telegram-bot.log'

# --- Telegram notifier + Q&A bot (optional) ---
# Leave unset to disable the feature entirely; the ping script and the
# Q&A daemon both no-op cleanly without these.

# Bot token from @BotFather (Telegram) — keep secret.
# TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN='123456789:AAExampleTokenReplaceMe'

# Your numeric Telegram chat id (get it via getUpdates after messaging
# your bot once — see README for the exact steps).
# TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID='987654321'

# OpenAI API key, used only as a fallback for free-form questions the
# Q&A bot doesn't recognize as a known schedule question.
# OPENAI_API_KEY='sk-exampleReplaceMe'

# Optional: override the OpenAI model used for that fallback.
# OPENAI_MODEL='gpt-5-nano'
